9 emotional responses have become increasingly valuable to businesses.<br><br>Aggregate feedback from Emoticash partners indicates a 17% increase in consumer engagement with brands through EDR feedback interfaces as opposed to traditional feedback forms and questionnaires. On the consumer side, similar uptakes in performance and engagement have been recorded; Emoticash users, on average, engage with brands and businesses 13% more than they did previously, and have shown an increase in general satisfaction with their consumer experiences.&nbsp;<br><br>Early responses to Emoticash suggest a promising new avenue for interaction between businesses and consumers is emerging, providing consumers with greater purchasing power, and businesses with vital data which will help them to evaluate their business practices and provide better services to their customers.&nbsp;<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}},\"1051\":{\"type\":\"image\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"file\":[\"1050\"],\"size\":\"large\"}}},\"52\":\"Welcome to Emoticash, where we bring your feelings into the equation. We believe that consumers should be rewarded for sharing their emotional data. It takes 26 muscles to smile, or 62 to frown. We accept either as payment.\",\"37\":[\"1048\"]}}', '2018-03-28 11:06:01', '2018-03-28 11:06:01', '3734408d-938b-42e5-ab41-c0e3d12f634b'),
 ('688', '1022', '4', '1', 'en_us', '22', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"EMOTICASH: FINANCE WITH FEELING\",\"slug\":\"emoticash-finance-with-feeling\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"53\":{\"1023\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p>In the age of mass surveillance where every street corner is manned by a security camera and every financial transaction is tracked by dozens of algorithms, consumers have long grown used to being watched. Many view the information exchange between citizen and state that underpins our modern surveillance system as a necessary evil for public safety.<br><br>But one area where, until only a few years ago, the transactional nature of surveillance had not yet been fully explored was in the growing Emotional Detection and Recognition (EDR) technology market \\u2013 the tracking of human emotions and reactions in industries where such data is vital, for example retail, hospitality and healthcare.<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}},\"1024\":{\"type\":\"image\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"file\":[\"1026\"],\"size\":\"large\"}},\"1025\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p>Using EDR technology, brands and businesses are now able to harvest the raw data of their customers\\u2019 emotive responses to their products and services. But little has been asked of how customers would be reimbursed for this new degree of data collection. Put another way, if they\\u2019re already paying for goods and services with cash, but are providing valuable emotional and affective information on top - how should they be compensated?<br><br>First introduced by Superimpose Studio, Emoticash (EMOT) aims to answer some of these questions. An evolution of the algorithm employed by popular cryptocurrencies such as Bitcoin (BTC) and Ethereum (ETH), Emoticash seeks to reimburse consumers with spendable currency whenever their emotional information 