 ('737', '1107', '4', '1', 'en_us', '1', '', '{\"typeId\":null,\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"EMOTICASH RESPONSE #2\",\"slug\":\"emoticash-response-2\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"53\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p><em>\\u201cAre we being too intrusive? Will these technologies be exploited? Will we lose our sense of self?\\u201d<br><br><\\/em>This technological use to map and read emotions seems quite intriguing as from reading the questions my mind polarises 3 different scenarios.<\\/p><p>Commercial exploitation: One in which your grin activates advertising that targets a particular weakness and has you buy more of that \\\"healing promise product\\\". In this scenario enterprises target individual aspirations in a crafted and refined way, similarly to the way web ads appear as a pair to your recent web browsing history yet a lot more subtle and efficient.<br><br>Institutional\\/Militarised exploitation: In our hyper-vigilant society, facial expressions surely are being used to determinate who is a threat to society. The uses of these readings could be used in court to determine someone\'s veracity or psychological state. Or simply to determine a the positive or negative societal value of an individual regarding their average emotional state.<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}}},\"52\":\"\",\"37\":\"\"}}', '2018-04-18 10:44:50', '2018-04-18 10:44:50', '7bec4179-abe9-4d76-b130-d478e96c6aa9'),
