 ('739', '1107', '4', '1', 'en_us', '3', '', '{\"typeId\":\"4\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"EMOTICASH RESPONSE #2\",\"slug\":\"emoticash-response-2\",\"postDate\":null,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":0,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"53\":{\"1108\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p><em>\\u201cAre we being too intrusive? Will these technologies be exploited? Will we lose our sense of self?\\u201d<br><br><\\/em>This technological use to map and read emotions seems quite intriguing as from reading the questions my mind polarises 3 different scenarios...<br><br><strong>Commercial exploitation<br><\\/strong>One in which your grin activates advertising that targets a particular weakness and has you buy more of that \\\"healing promise product\\\". In this scenario enterprises target individual aspirations in a crafted and refined way, similarly to the way web ads appear as a pair to your recent web browsing history yet a lot more subtle and efficient.<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}},\"new1\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p><strong>Institutional\\/Militarised exploitation&nbsp;<br><\\/strong>In our hyper-vigilant society, facial expressions surely are being used to determinate who is a threat to society. The uses of these readings could be used in court to determine someone\'s veracity or psychological state. Or simply to determine a the positive or negative societal value of an individual regarding their average emotional state.<span><\\/span><span><\\/span><\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p><strong>Institutional\\/Health purposes<\\/strong>&nbsp;<br>We live at the verge of the clog in public healthcare being massively relieved by the use of AI. We are also currently living in an age where anxiety and adverse mental health is on the rise. Despite several organisations offering counselling at a low cost or free, the majority of people who seek emotional\\/ psychological help, heavily rely on private counsellors. Facial recognition as an addition to an AI counselling service could prove highly beneficial, as the bot could recognise patterns not only on speech rhythm, intonation and breath, but also facial expressions that could compose a better profile and\\/or trigger the questions that the patient needs to seek answers to. &nbsp;&nbsp;All of this at a fraction of the cost of a regular therapy session, with, hopefully, same or better results a face to face therapy. NOTE: This exercise should be attached to a non exploitative confidential agreement between the software developers, researchers and patients. This would be the ideal use of emotion-recognition.<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"copy\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"copy\":\"<p>All technology is intrusive, as well as most policies are intrusive too, we humans have enormous capabilities to adapt and register something unusual, as part of our new routine in a matter of days. Whichever of these scenarios would happen, the truth is that, these will be adopted by us in the long term. It is simply the way our minds work.<br><br>I find that one loses oneself when one is out of touch with oneself, the first two proposed scenarios would help the weakening of the individual, as in the smart advertising scenario, this technology seeks to understand, target and exploit the reactionary nature of human beings.<br><br>The second scenario, provides that the individual envelops him\\/herself in a mask of normality and cannoned behaviour, diluting their personality.<br><br>The third use, if used within non exploitative parameters, will help the individual know and understand themselves better, and will become a tool for healing and self discovery rather than an extra layer with which curate oneself, or a new channel with which to cloud people\'s existence.<\\/p>\",\"position\":\"full\"}}},\"52\":\"\",\"37\":\"\"}}', '2018-04-18 10:47:39', '